metadata.name: Alleles #284
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

attributes.name: Genetic Profile
attributes.value: Preliminary analysis of the information provided suggests subject experiences frequent episodes of negative self-imagery and lack of self-confidence, yet also has the potential to display a high degree of loyalty and leadership. Maximum potential hereditary height (excluding nutritional and environmental factors) is estimated at 197-203cm. Projected natural lifespan estimated at 92-92 years.

metadata.name: Pixel Tunneling #154
metadata.description:
This is based on a technique I've used to create textured abstract art based by starting with a base design and applying millions of small mutations. Each design has a minimum of 3,000,000 mutations and as many as 10,000,000 mutations.

- Higher themes are more rare (25 max)
- Higher patterns are more rare (10 max)
- Chaos odds (medium=85%, low=10%, high=5%)
- Blend odds (medium=85%, low=10%, high=5%)

metadata.name: The Circuit Cure #25
metadata.description:
When tech fails there’s a cure – The Circuit Cure. This is a series of 100 animated GENTKs on fxhash that draws inspiration from 80s video games and a seminal cyberpunk movie franchise. Each artwork features two randomly chosen circuit board designs in a variety of colors. The medicine comes to the rescue in blue pills, red pills, or the very rare yellow pills.

Rarity includes:
– 2 out of 6 random circuit board designs
– 2 out of 9 random circuit board colors
– Falling Blue (55% chance), Red (40% chance), or Yellow pills (5% chance)

Genesis GENTK by @3amkind & @levoontin.

metadata.name: Spira #18
metadata.description:
Spira is a series of static pieces where lines are drawn symmetrically around a central pivot. Additionally it is possible for the piece to be "broken" in which case some of the symmetry is lost and instead a more complex asymmetrical piece is produced.

Features:
> Brokenness (A percentage to indicate how "broken" the piece is.)
> Rotation (Rotation of each iteration.)
> Palette (Colour palette.)
> Sectors (Number of sectors which form the rotational symmetry.)
> Iterations (Number of iterations - higher means more lines in each sector.)
> Spacing (The spacing between each iteration.)

Created by Lucas RiedlShah (@lucas_riedlshah)

metadata.name: Dynamic generations #154
metadata.description:
A classic cellular automata updates its state with a static rule based on the state of its neighbor.

This collection was created with cellular automata with an extension of that idea. Here the state and the rule are updated based on the state of its neighbor, here the rule changes in every iteration, here the rule is dynamic.

That change moves cellular automata to another level of complexity.

metadata.name: AN2: Recuerdos  #36
metadata.description:
"AN2: Recuerdos" is an abstract collection that is the direct sequel to Artificialmente Natural. Recuerdos are memories in Spanish, and with this collection, I tried to evoke specifically that, a memory. There are many times throughout our life that our memory changes and grow. Sometimes we even alter memories unconsciously, mixing them up between other memories and even fantasy or dreams (ever had a Deja Vu?), creating a new memory solely based on an idea of the past and what it was. We live in a world of perceptions, and that is exactly what our memory is, a combination of perceptions that became ideas, made up of other older ideas and new ones, to then get stored inside our brain as new memories.

Now, you may ask, cool story, but what does it have to do with the collection? Well, through your memories, experiences, and perceptions, you're going to analyze the piece. You may think you see an abstract ocean in the background, or a sky, or waves, or auras. You may feel that the art piece sometimes looks decayed, splattered with paint, or just splattered with dirty noise. The truth is that through your memory, you're going to try to make sense of it no matter if you like what you're seeing or not, and that's the sole idea of everything. Interpreting through our experiences is how we calm the tension we feel from the unknown. You can't make a comparison or an interpretation if you haven't seen or experienced something that laid an idea inside your brain, becoming multiple other ideas through plasticity and neural connectivity, always trying to make sense of everything. That's why your "recuerdos" is the key to the way you interpret life and live it, both unconsciously and consciously. 

For me, this collection consciously reminds me of my teenage years. A little chaotic at times, with some beautiful moments of self-discovery. Mistakes were made, love was found and lost, and everything was pretty colorful and new. Unconsciously, I don't know, that's the beauty of the unknown. 

--------------------------------------------------------------

NOTICE

Allow list will be deleted 48 hours after the collections goes live.

--------------------------------------------------------------
FYI

Loading of the art goes through 3 stages in order. It may take between 30 seconds to 40 seconds to finalize.

-------------------------------------------------------------

Press [S] to save as PNG

metadata.name: Mythologic #192
metadata.description:
"Mythologic" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022.

Mythologic is a project derived from cloud series, Cloud Atlas and Requiem: Cloud on fxhash. In the series, lines and circles are used in an organics movement like Cloud Hands, which is a move of Tai Chi. Practitioners move their hands slowly and smoothly, make circles and rotate with extreme concentrating. In Chinese we said “floating clouds and flowing water” to describe calligraphers’ freely flowing style of writing. Chi is a very important for oriental artists, and for genart as well. In the series, lines and circles start from one position to another, and develop with organic rotations and movements, like practicing Tai Chi on the canvas. 

Mythologic was inspired from “Classic of Mountains and Seas”, also known as Shan Hai Jing, is a Chinese classic text and a compilation of mythic geography and beasts. 

“There is a beast that looks like a fox with nine tails.” 
“Huangbei: it is a beetle with meat like a tadpole, but with a head and a tail” 
“The beast has the body of a fish but the wings of a bird” 

There are many incredible creatures in the text which describe the oriental fantasy. The idea of Mythologic is to present an illustrated handbook with random generated paintings, each one is like a framed badge, to memorize the glorious age. It uses the "cloud hands" technique in every parts of this piece, the center, the circle and the frame. They are all the same algorithm but perform variety with different density and components. Gold, Silver, Copper, Jade and Ruby colors as noble symbol of treasure in Chinese culture. 

This project use p5js. 

Press 'S' to save pictures.

Thanks to the support of Yi-Wen Lin in this project.
